{
  "topic": "Whether a three-layer behavioral review system is an appropriate replacement/supplement for traditional code review in AI-assisted development contexts",
  "perspectives": [
    {
      "id": "traditional-review",
      "label": "Traditional Code Review Advocate",
      "coreClaim": "Line-by-line code review remains the gold standard for catching defects, transferring implementation knowledge, and maintaining engineering rigor, and cannot be safely deprioritized even when code is AI-generated.",
      "supportingArguments": [
        "Serendipitous bug discovery — reviewers noticing 'what happens if X?' — catches entire classes of defects that behavioral testing misses by design.",
        "Deep implementation knowledge transfer is essential for bus-factor resilience; reviewers who only know what the product does cannot maintain or extend unfamiliar subsystems.",
        "Behavioral verification only catches problems that manifest observably; security vulnerabilities, race conditions, memory leaks, and architectural decay are often invisible at the surface.",
        "Trust in automated layers (CI, LLM adversarial review) is itself unvalidated — a reviewer who cannot read code cannot audit whether automation is functioning correctly."
      ],
      "vulnerabilities": [
        "Reviewer effort scales linearly with change volume, making it unsustainable at AI-assisted development velocity.",
        "Reviewers who are not fluent in the libraries or language features used cannot meaningfully assess AI-generated code, producing the appearance of review without the substance.",
        "The document's own admission that 'code review of AI-generated code in unfamiliar libraries provides the appearance of serendipitous discovery without the reality' directly undermines this position's practical force.",
        "Traditional review conflates verification of correctness with communication of state — the behavioral system separates these, potentially handling both more explicitly."
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "behavioral-primary",
      "label": "Behavioral Review Advocate",
      "coreClaim": "When most code is AI-generated and reviewers lack library fluency, behavioral review — experiencing the product as a user — is the most honest and scalable form of oversight available, supplemented by automation for correctness.",
      "supportingArguments": [
        "Reviewer effort grows sublinearly with change volume: a structured walkthrough of observable behaviors scales independently of implementation complexity.",
        "Behavioral verification catches the defect classes that actually reach users: UX problems, workflow failures, miscommunication between author and product.",
        "Separating specification (human-defined test cases) from implementation (AI-generated test code) breaks the circular validation trap without requiring reviewers to read unfamiliar code.",
        "The dual-purpose documentation model — review queue feeding an onboarding guide — simultaneously serves communication, onboarding, and verification goals that traditional review conflates without serving well."
      ],
      "vulnerabilities": [
        "The author curates the walkthrough, creating a systematic conflict of interest: the person with the most incentive to minimize scrutiny controls what gets scrutinized.",
        "Rubber-stamping is a social risk the system cannot fully prevent through tooling alone; it depends on reviewer engagement that cannot be mandated.",
        "Bus factor risk increases materially: no reviewer develops implementation-level understanding sufficient to maintain or debug unfamiliar subsystems.",
        "The system is explicitly not self-stabilizing and will degrade toward automation-only review over 6-12 months without active maintenance — this fragility is a structural weakness."
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "automation-only",
      "label": "Automation-First Advocate",
      "coreClaim": "With sufficiently robust CI pipelines, adversarial LLM review, coverage thresholds, and mutation testing, human review of AI-generated code adds more process overhead than defect-catching value.",
      "supportingArguments": [
        "Automated systems are tireless, consistent, and scale perfectly with change volume without degrading under review fatigue.",
        "Multi-model adversarial review can catch logic errors, security issues, and architectural inconsistencies faster and more reliably than a human unfamiliar with the codebase.",
        "Formal specifications verified by CI provide stronger trust guarantees than behavioral walkthroughs or code review alone.",
        "Human review introduces social dynamics — rubber-stamping, reluctance to challenge, relationship management — that automation avoids."
      ],
      "vulnerabilities": [
        "Automation cannot serve the communication purpose of review: the reviewer needs to experience the product to remain current on what it does and why.",
        "Automated tests only verify what has been specified; they cannot catch defects in the specification itself or emergent UX failures.",
        "Fully automated pipelines lose the onboarding function: new team members and users have no human-maintained artifact explaining what the product does.",
        "The circular validation trap — AI writes code and tests, both reflecting the same misunderstanding — is not broken by adding more automation; it requires human specification of edge cases and failure modes."
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "risk-gating",
      "label": "Risk-Tiered Review Advocate",
      "coreClaim": "Review effort should be allocated strictly by risk classification: high-risk changes (auth, schemas, infrastructure) receive mandatory code review; low-risk changes receive automated checks only, with no behavioral layer.",
      "supportingArguments": [
        "Reviewers have limited attention; concentrating it where defects are most consequential maximizes risk reduction per unit of reviewer time.",
        "Risk classification is tractable to automate: changes to auth/, migrations/, and infrastructure configs can be flagged by CI without author self-reporting.",
        "Eliminating behavioral review for routine changes removes a layer that is vulnerable to rubber-stamping and author curation bias.",
        "The communication and onboarding goals of review can be served by documentation practices decoupled from the review process itself."
      ],
      "vulnerabilities": [
        "Risk classification of low-risk changes is precisely where behavioral defects accumulate invisibly — UX failures, workflow gaps, and feature miscommunications concentrate in 'routine' changes.",
        "Decoupling communication from review removes the forcing function that keeps co-developers current on product state; documentation maintained voluntarily degrades faster than documentation tied to the review process.",
        "The approach loses the dual-purpose walkthrough artifact, requiring separate investment in onboarding documentation that is unlikely to happen in a small team.",
        "Author self-classification of change risk is manipulable; without behavioral spot checks as an external check, classification drift is undetectable until a post-merge incident."
      ]
    }
  ],
  "tensions": [
    {
      "between": ["traditional-review", "behavioral-primary"],
      "description": "Core tradeoff between depth and scalability: traditional review provides implementation-level understanding and serendipitous discovery but cannot scale to AI-assisted development velocity or reviewer unfamiliarity; behavioral review scales and catches user-facing defects but weakens implementation knowledge transfer and is blind to non-behavioral defects by design."
    },
    {
      "between": ["behavioral-primary", "automation-only"],
      "description": "Disagreement about the necessity of human behavioral verification: the behavioral advocate insists human experience of the product is irreplaceable for communication, onboarding, and UX defect detection; the automation advocate argues these goals are either served by tooling or should be served by separate documentation practices rather than review."
    },
    {
      "between": ["traditional-review", "automation-only"],
      "description": "Both perspectives claim to catch defects the other misses, but disagree on whether human judgment or computational exhaustiveness is more reliable for AI-generated code — the traditional reviewer cannot assess unfamiliar library code meaningfully; the automated pipeline cannot assess specification correctness or emergent UX behavior."
    },
    {
      "between": ["behavioral-primary", "risk-gating"],
      "description": "Structural disagreement about where routine-change oversight should reside: behavioral review advocates argue UX and communication defects accumulate in routine changes and require a dedicated layer; risk-gating advocates argue reviewer attention is better concentrated on high-consequence changes, with routine changes handled by automation."
    },
    {
      "between": ["risk-gating", "automation-only"],
      "description": "Agreement that human review should be concentrated or eliminated for routine changes, but disagreement about whether high-risk changes justify mandatory code review (risk-gating) or whether adversarial LLM review is sufficient even for auth and infrastructure changes (automation-only)."
    }
  ],
  "synthesis": {
    "equilibrium": "The three-layer system as proposed represents a genuine equilibrium, but its stability depends on three conditions that the document acknowledges but does not fully resolve: (1) explicit social contract negotiation rather than assumed agreement, (2) the spot-check mechanism being treated as mandatory rather than aspirational, and (3) the walkthrough curation conflict of interest being mitigated by diff-coverage automation rather than author honesty alone. The synthesized position is: behavioral review is the appropriate primary mode for routine changes precisely because it is more honest about what reviewers can actually verify in AI-assisted development — but it must be bracketed by automation (Layer 1) that is trusted only because humans specify its test cases, and by structural review (Layer 3) that is triggered by risk classification and preserved by random spot checks. The system does not maximize any single value (depth, scalability, automation, risk reduction) but provides a defensible minimum across all of them. Its known losses — serendipitous discovery, deep implementation knowledge, author as single point of failure — are accepted as honest costs of operating in an AI-assisted development context, not dismissed as solved problems.",
    "howAddressed": [
      {
        "perspectiveId": "traditional-review",
        "resolution": "Implementation knowledge transfer and serendipitous discovery are preserved through mandatory Layer 3 review for high-risk change types, monthly architectural review sessions, and the 1-in-10 spot check norm that keeps reviewers capable of reading code and builds implementation understanding incrementally over time. The system does not eliminate code review — it restructures when it is required and makes that requirement enforceable by CI risk classification rather than reviewer discretion."
      },
      {
        "perspectiveId": "behavioral-primary",
        "resolution": "Behavioral review is established as the primary mode for routine feature changes, with the reviewer's role explicitly reframed as user acceptance testing rather than correctness verification. The dual-purpose walkthrough artifact serves both the review queue and the onboarding guide, giving behavioral review a concrete deliverable beyond approval. The escalation path to code review is preserved as an always-available option, not a separate request process, ensuring behavioral review is a lens rather than a wall."
      },
      {
        "perspectiveId": "automation-only",
        "resolution": "Layer 1 automation is treated as a prerequisite rather than an afterthought: CI, coverage thresholds, adversarial LLM review, and mutation testing are Phase 0 infrastructure. The formalization bootstrapping path (Phase 3) explicitly moves high-value behavioral properties from manual walkthroughs to machine-checked specifications, giving automation an expanding scope as product capabilities mature. The system does not resist automation — it channels it into the layer where it is most reliable and most auditable."
      },
      {
        "perspectiveId": "risk-gating",
        "resolution": "Risk-tiered mandatory code review is fully incorporated as Layer 3, with CI-automated classification for high-risk change types (auth, migrations, infrastructure, API boundaries) and decision documents required for the highest-risk categories. The behavioral layer is not applied universally — the change-type table explicitly shows which changes require behavioral-only review versus behavioral-plus-structural versus mandatory code review. Risk gating is the structure of Layer 3, not an alternative to the system."
      }
    ]
  },
  "summary": "The source document proposes a three-layer review system for AI-assisted development that restructures traditional code review into automation (correctness, regressions), behavioral verification (UX, workflow, communication), and structural review (security, architecture, high-risk changes). The central dialectical tension is between scalability and depth: traditional code review cannot scale to AI-assisted velocity or reviewer unfamiliarity, but abandoning it risks blind spots in security, architecture, and implementation knowledge transfer. The proposed system resolves this not by choosing a winner but by assigning different defect classes to different layers — accepting known losses (serendipitous discovery, bus factor, author as single point of failure) as honest costs rather than dismissed risks. The system's stability depends critically on social contract negotiation, mandatory spot checks, and diff-coverage automation to counter the walkthrough curation conflict of interest — without these, the document's own analysis predicts degradation toward automation-only review within 6-12 months."
}
```

